</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=robaz>Robaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 200<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/23/03 5:17:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4063.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Where is the money coming from?</span><hr size=1> I have been attempting to raise money as my frail cleric is lagging behind in equipment.  I even had someone ask to inspect, inspect, then laugh at my equipment recently which is what sparked this newfound goal to improve myself.  I am starting to learn what it takes to make money.<br>
<br>
A few things I have learned:<br>
<br>
1.  Be the first to get something new - As has been previously stated, being the first to have something new is a great benefit.  Everyone will want them.  I remember when PoP came out and people were scrambling like mad to get Ethereal Parchments, and the spells were expensive, some in the 10k range.  Now when they drop most people are not even interested.  I see the same thing happening eventually with spectrals as more people and guilds gather the 63-65 spells up.<br>
<br>
2.  You really are not going to make any money unless you are 50+.  Well at least not without a LOT of hard work.  I tried selling things pre 50 and nothing I could make, aquire or trade for had much value and the things I could make with my tradeskill (baking) sometimes netted an ok profit, it was just not worth the time.  I still have nightmares about Halas Pie combines.<br>
<br>
3.  If you are not guilded, it can hinder making money.  Since I have been unguilded I have noticed that I have not gotten any good upgrades in a long time.  Occasionally I will stumble on a decent item to upgrade with but it is rare, and the item I am replacing is often not that valuable.  I bought my Lodizial shell shield a while ago for over 24k I think and I saw one  for 17K in /auc the other day.   If I get a replacement item for that, I have already lost 7k.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
4.  One good thing I have learned is that when a new tradeskill uber item is discovered, you can often make lots of plat if you can get the sub ingredients and sell them.  For example, Metallic Liquid, Iksar Blood, Pristine Tae Ew Scales, Tae Ew Blood Vial.  All of these items currently fetch decent amounts.  I had been saving them up to have someone make me some armor, but I have sold enough of the sub ingredients for my Tae Ew Shield to buy the shield and still have money left over.  <br>
<br>
5.  Farm Vendors.  A long time ago I got 250 baking and when I was done I saw other players /auc ing for various baking ingredients.  I farmed some vendors in Gfay for example, and on one vendor I got like 8 stacks of cinnamon sticks that at that time were selling for 50-100p a stack.  Not a huge sum of money, but the percentage on my return was GREAT.  You just have to know what to farm and catch a lucky break now and then.  I remember seeing razorfiend talons on vendors for uber cheap cause no one knew what they were for when PoP first came out, wish I had saved them up.<br>
<br>
6.  CT.  There are tons of money making drops in CT, and I have been trying to spend more time there.  Sometimes you get nothing, other days you can net 50-100k if you are lucky enough to get the Boots of Flowing slime or the Fleshgrinder.  I actually got a fleshgrinder a long time ago, but gave it away to someone who needed it.  So it can happen, just gotta fix them dice.  =)  Good luck friend.<br>
<br>
Robaz<br>
Vazaelle<br>
